title: For Sale:  Taurus 24/7 OSS DS Tactical 9mm
postcontent: I'm selling my Taurus 9mm 24/7 OSS DS Tactical. (NRA) Handgun of the Year award in 2005. The OSS models feature a 5.25 inch match grade forged barrel and a 3 position safety system - the bottom position enables the pistol to fire, the middle setting puts it in 'safe' condition, and the upper decocks the striker. This arrangement results in several carry options for the user as the gun can be carried with a round in the chamber ‘cocked and locked’ in ‘condition one’ (striker cocked with safety on), or the arguably safer ‘Condition Two’ (striker decocked and safety off, requiring a revolver-like DA pull to both cock and fire the pistol), or even with the striker decocked and the safety on. The OSS retains the loaded chamger indicator of the other 24/7 models, and additionally allows visual verification that the pistol is ready to fire as the striker can be seen when the pistol is cocked. Asking $360.00 cash no trades.

title: For Sale:  Colt 1st Generation SAA Single Action 5.5" .41 Colt c. 1900 w/Holster Rig & Letter
postcontent: A very good condition Colt Single Action Army Revolver with almost new bore. This Colt was shipped to Simmons Hardware July 23, 1900, in the configuration you see (5.5" barrel, .41 Colt, hard rubber grips). A note from a previous owner dated October, 2011, says he purchased it from Texas through a magazine ad in the summer of 1955. He sent it in to Colt for "re-barreling and conditioning". From the appearance of the gun today, the cylinder, back strap and trigger guard were re-blued and the barrel, ejector housing and cylinder pin were replaced. It also locks up tight. Since that was before the 2nd generation guns reached production, that would account for the almost new, 1st generation, .41 Colt barrel and newer finish on the ejector housing. He states further that "...It is very accurate as I occasionally shot squirrels and ground hogs with it. The last one being a squirrel high in a hickory tree using hand loads with bullets I cast about 1975...".  The gun has been test fired with no problems. The Colt is housed in a basket weave carved, rawhide laced, holster and 26 loop cartridge belt stamped "Eubanks Leather, Boise,  There is a place at the toe of the holster where the leather has torn through next to the lacing. Otherwise, the leather is supple and in good condition.Our prices reflect a 4% discount for cash or certified funds (Cashier’s Check, USPS Money Order , Western Union or Moneygram).
